<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1894-04-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1894-04-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="171" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d171">
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Gresham</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Bayard</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1894-04-04"><hi rend="italic">April 4,
                            1894</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                    <p>Bill which passed Senate yesterday contains nothing but provisions for
                        enforcement of regulations. House committee unanimously instructed its
                        chairman to move suspension of rules and pass bill immediately. At all
                        events, bill will be a law this week.</p>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>